<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>9 SPEED AND 11 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS EATON RTO-1X707LL/DLL/MLL AND RTO-1X709MLL MODELS - REMOVE - COUNTERSHAFT
        BEARINGS
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="7">
        <title>COUNTERSHAFT BEARINGS</title>
        <para>The following instructions are used to remove the upper and lower countershaft bearings. To remove the
            mainshaft assembly, only the upper countershaft bearings need to be removed.
        </para>
        <specpara>
            <caution>
                <para>Performing the following instructions will damage the bearings and should not be done unless
                    bearing replacement is planned.
                </para>
            </caution>
        </specpara>
        <para>The bearing inner race remains pressed on the countershaft after removal of the front bearings.</para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the snap ring from each countershaft rear groove (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302044">Figure 44</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302044" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302044" filename="../figg13/g1302044.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 44. Snap Ring</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">From inside the case, use a soft bar and maul to drive the countershaft rear bearings from
                the case bores (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302045">Figure 45</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302045" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302045" filename="../figg13/g1302045.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 45. Countershaft Rear Bearings</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the bolt and front retainer plate from each countershaft (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302046">Figure 46</hotlnk>and
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302047">Figure 47</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302046" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302046" filename="../figg13/g1302046.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 46. Bolt &#38; Front Retainer Plate</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f1302047" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302047" filename="../figg13/g1302047.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 47. Bolt &#38; Front Retainer Plate</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use the soft bar and maul to drive each countershaft to the rear as far as possible (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302048">Figure 48</hotlnk>). This partially unseats the front bearings.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302048" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302048" filename="../figg13/g1302048.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 48. Front Bearings</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">From the case rear, drive each countershaft forward as far as possible (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302049">Figure 49</hotlnk>). This exposes the bearing snap rings.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302049" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302049" filename="../figg13/g1302049.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 49. Bearing Snap Rings</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a bearing puller or pry bars to remove the countershaft front bearings (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1302050">Figure 50</hotlnk>). If a bearing puller is used, the front bearing cover has
                to be removed.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1302050" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1302050" filename="../figg13/g1302050.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 50. Bearing Puller</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
